revision.text:
[[File:Głębocki-Children.jpg|thumb|200px|Self-portrait with His Children (c.1870)]] '''Adrian Mikołaj Głębocki''' (8 September 1833, [[Panki, Silesian Voivodeship|Panki]] - 15 May 1905, [[Warsaw]]) was a Polish painter, lithographer and art teacher.
==Biography== After completing secondary school in 1850, he studied at the School of Fine Arts in Warsaw until 1857, where his primary instructor was [[Rafał Hadziewicz]]. This was followed by studies in Paris, Vienna and Munich. After completing his studies, he worked briefly in Warsaw as a scenery painter for the set designer, Antonio Sacchetti (1790–1870).<ref name="AA">[http://www.agraart.pl/cgi-bin/obiekt.cgi?act=1&qt=1462656852&nr=12225 Biographical notes] @ Agra Art.</ref> From 1863, he lived in [[Częstochowa]], where he taught at the local [[Gymnasium (school)|gymnasium]]. [[File:Głębocki-JasnaGora.jpg|thumb|350px|Pilgrims Arriving at Jasna Góra]] During this time, he created numerous works related to the [[Kalisz Region]]. Many of the buildings he depicted no longer exist, so his paintings have acquired great documentary value. His work includes an album of 52 watercolors of the [[Jasna Góra Monastery]] and the ceremonies there. He often accompanied his works with descriptions and commentary, and wrote several articles on the monuments of the region.<ref name="A">[http://www.absolwenci.sieniu.czest.pl/index.php?show=art&which=665 Brief biography] @ Absolwenci Sienkiewicza.</ref>
In 1873, he moved to Warsaw. There, he began to provide illustrations for ''Kłosach'' (Ears), ''{{ill|Biesiada Literacka|pl}}'' (Literary Feast) and the ''[[Tygodnik Ilustrowany]]''. He also wrote a major article about his work in Częstochowa for the literary journal ''Wiek'' and continued teaching at a school for the deaf as well as giving private lessons.<ref name="AA" />
Many of his lithographs are arranged in "cycles" on religious and historical themes. He also produced several art books for children, including some with cut-out patterns for toys.<ref name="A" />
