{{refimprove|date=July 2018}}
'''Korean animation''', '''Korean anime''', '''manga animasyonu''', or '''''aeni''''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|æ|n|i|}}; {{lang-ko|애니}}) has become an industry that produces characters for other countries' companies, exports its creations globally and generates billions of dollars in profits.
==History== [[File:Animation character Lava.jpg|thumb|Larva in the [[Lotte World II Hotel]]]]
{{main|History of Korean animation}}
The Korean animation industry was in a period of crisis throughout the 2000s. Depression at the reality of being an industry that the West merely gave factory-type drawing to began to sink in. This followed the 1990s, a period of explosive growth for the industry when Korean studios made most of their profits from OEM, mostly from the United States.{{Citation needed|date=January 2017}}
In many ways, 2011 was a bright transitional year for Korean animation, with home-produced animated feature films finally finding box office success in South Korea, instead of facing the usual financial failure. As far as overseas export market is concerned, the likes of [[Rough Draft Korea]] (RDK) kept on landing new contracts, which have seen Rough Draft perform the manual work on over 45 popular Western cartoon titles over 16 years.<ref name=korazy>{{cite web |url=http://www.korazy.com.au/main/page_articles_article_2.html |title=Korazy Art Exhibit |publisher=Korazy.com.au |date= |accessdate=2012-05-23 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426054727/http://www.korazy.com.au/main/page_articles_article_2.html |archivedate=2012-04-26 |df= }}</ref>
Korean animation has boomed in popularity in Eastern Asia with the success of the series ''[[Pororo the Little Penguin]]'' and ''[[Origami Warriors#Adaptation|Origami Warriors]]'' in 2011, leaving fans wanting to discover more Korean animations. This success is due in part to perfecting the Korean animation technique, and financial returns being reinvested into new animated products.{{Citation needed|date=January 2017}}
Some Korean animators still blame the booming Korean game industry for draining the animation industry's talent pool,{{ref|manhwa1}} but the box office success of the Korean animated film ''[[Leafie]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/finecut-sells-animated-leafie-us-265085 |title=Finecut Sells Animated 'Leafie' to U.S., U.K., Australia |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=2011-11-22 |accessdate=2012-05-23}}</ref> in 2011 in South Korea is inspiring a new generation.{{citation needed|date=May 2012}}
==Animation industry== Animation contracts for Korean animation studios range from collaboration/minor contribution contracts, to most of the work. The South Korean animation industry can be considered dynamic as there are more than a hundred animation studios. While it is mostly firms in South Korea that contract with Western studios, some of the work is reported to be subcontracted to [[North Korea]] as well.{{ref|sunny-lee}}
===Korean animation characters in public spaces=== [[File:루돌프 타요.JPG|thumb|Tayo bus 'Rudolph']]
*'''Larva subway''' was a subway based on and featured a [[Larva (TV series)|Larva]] character. It operated from November 2014 until May 2015 on line No. 2. The Seoul government and Metro explained that they wanted to give citizens a chance to celebrate the 40th anniversary of the subways opening.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsis.com/ar_detail/view.html?ar_id=NISX20150529_0013694809&cID=10201&pID=10200|title=지하철 2호선 '라바 열차', 이달 운행 종료|last=Gang|first=Jieun|date=2015-05-29|work=|publisher=Newsis|publication-date=2015-05-29|trans-title='Larve subway' on line No.2. End of this month|access-date=|via=}}</ref> *'''Tayo buses''' were organized by the [[Seoul Metropolitan Government]], the Bus Transport Business Association, and the animation company which made [[Tayo the Little Bus]] for the Public Transportation Day. In 2014, the [[Seoul Metropolitan Government]] commissioned buses designed as the characters of Tayo the Little Bus to go around the [[Gwanghwamun Square]] area of the city.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.businesspost.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=7984|title=서울시‘타요버스’, 이렇게 찾아요|last=Oh|first=Wonseok|date=2014-04-02|work=|publisher=Bloter|publication-date=2014-04-02|trans-title='Tayo bus' of Seoul city, find this way|access-date=|via=}}</ref> *In 2014, statues of Larva and Pororo the Little Penguin were installed in World Park, which is a square in the [[Lotte World II Hotel]]. They were well received by citizens and tourist.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://view.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?idxno=2014103113130273745|title=롯데월드몰, 그랜드 오픈 기념 이벤트 풍성|last=Song|first=Hwajung|date=2014-10-31|work=|publisher=Asia Economy|publication-date=2014-10-31|trans-title=Lotte world mall grand open was well received|access-date=|via=}}</ref>
==Market== In 2010, according to the [[Korea Creative Content Agency]], the Korean market share of domestic characters was about 28% and the remaining 72% was for foreign characters, such as those from Japan and USA. In 2012, experts predicted that the total market size would grow to 10 trillion won (about 9 billion dollars in July 2018) in the near future .<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.businesspost.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=7984|title=8조 캐릭터 시장, 도약하는 토종 캐릭터|last=Oh|first=Daeseok|date=2014-12-28|work=|access-date=|publisher=Business Post|publication-date=2014-12-28|trans-title=8 billion character market, Growing domestic character|via=}}</ref> In 2014, the domestic character market share soared to 40% and its value in 2013 had reached 8 trillion [[South Korean won|won]] (about 7 billion dollars).
=== Korean characters as international business === Before the emergence of Korean domestic [[character (arts)|character]]s, characters that enjoyed popularity were mostly from the United States and [[Japan]].<ref name=":22">{{Cite journal|last=Hyeyoung Chu, hyunju Lee, Hyehyun Cho, Mirae Hwang|first=|date=Winter 2014|title=Periodic Features of Korean Character Designs|url=http://aodr.org/xml/01492/01492.pdf|journal=3.1 Period of Published Cartoon Characters (1980s~1990s)|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> However, as the industry matured and grew in size, domestic characters received preference not just domestically but also internationally.
