{{Infobox building | name = Lawang Sewu | native_name = | native_name_lang = | former_names = Administratiegebouw Nederlands-Indische Spoorweg Maatschappij | alternate_names = | status = | image = Lawang sewu.jpg | image_alt = | caption = Lawang Sewu in 2011 | map_type = Indonesia_Semarang | map_alt = Lawang Sewu | map_caption = Location in [[Semarang]] | altitude = | building_type = | architectural_style = | structural_system = | cost = | ren_cost = | client = | owner = [[Kereta Api Indonesia|Indonesian Railways]] | current_tenants = | landlord = | location = | address = Pemuda Street | location_town = [[Semarang]] | location_country = [[Indonesia]] | coordinates = {{coord|6|59|2.13|S|110|24|38.28|E|display=inline}} | groundbreaking_date = 1904 | start_date = | completion_date = 1919 | opened_date = 1907 | inauguration_date = | renovation_date = | height = | roof = | top_floor = | other_dimensions = | floor_count = 3 | floor_area = | seating_type = | seating_capacity = | main_contractor = | architect = [[Cosman Citroen|C. Citroen]] | architecture_firm = J.F. Klinkhamer and B.J. Quendag | structural_engineer = | services_engineer = | civil_engineer = | other_designers = | awards = | designations = | ren_architect = | ren_firm = | url = | embedded = | references = }} '''Lawang Sewu''' ("Thousand Doors") is a landmark in [[Semarang]], [[Central Java]], Indonesia, built as the headquarters of the [[Dutch East Indies Railway Company]]. The colonial era building is famous as a haunted house, though the Semarang city government has attempted to rebrand it.
==Etymology== The name Lawang Sewu is from [[Javanese language|Javanese]]; it means "Thousand Doors".{{sfn|Ariwibowo 2011, First Lady Inaugurates}} The name comes from its design, with numerous doors and arcs.{{sfn|Semarang City Government, Lawang Sewu}} The building has about 600 large windows.{{sfn|Rohmah 2013, Lawang Sewu}}
==Layout== [[File:Blueprints for Lawang Sewu.jpg|thumb|left|Blueprints for Building B]]
The complex consists of several buildings, two main ones named A and B and two smaller ones named C and D, on Pemuda Street.{{sfn|Prihadi 2011, Lawang Sewu Kini}}{{sfn|Semarang City Government, Lawang Sewu}} The l-shaped A building faces the Tugu Muda roundabout.{{sfn|Prihadi 2011, Lawang Sewu Kini}}{{sfn|Semarang City Government, Lawang Sewu}} There are two identical towers on A building, which were originally used to store water, each with a capacity of {{convert|7000|l|USgal}}.{{sfn|Prihadi 2011, Lawang Sewu Kini}} The building features large [[stained-glass windows]] and a grand staircase in the center.{{sfn|Gower 2009, Lawang Sewu: Ahaunted}} There was also once an underground tunnel connecting A building to several other sites in the city, including the governor's mansion and the harbour.{{sfn|Prihadi 2011, Lawang Sewu Kini}}
The B building is located behind A building.{{sfn|Prihadi 2011, Lawang Sewu Kini}} It is three stories in height, with the first two floors consisting of offices and the third holding a ballroom.{{sfn|Prihadi 2011, Lawang Sewu Kini}} The building, with high, large windows, also has a basement floor that is kept partially flooded to serve to cool the building through evaporation.{{sfn|Prihadi 2011, Lawang Sewu Kini}}
In front of A building stands a monument to five employees killed during the [[Indonesian War of Independence]].{{sfn|Tio|2011|p=62}} {{clearleft}} ==History== [[File:COLLECTIE TROPENMUSEUM Het hoofdkantoor van de Nederlandsch-Indische Spoorweg Maatschappij (NIS) in Semarang TMnr 10032316.jpg|thumb|left|"A Building" in the early 1900s]] [[File:Teak Table and Chairs in hall of Lawang Sewu, Semarang.jpg|thumb|left|A side hall of the building]]
Lawang Sewu was designed by [[Cosman Citroen]], from the firm of [[J.F. Klinkhamer]] and B.J. Quendag.{{sfn|Semarang City Government, Lawang Sewu}} It was designed in [[New Indies Style]], an academically-accepted term for [[Rationalism (architecture)|Dutch Rationalism]] in the Indies.<ref name=Heritage6-120>{{cite book |series=Indonesian Heritage |title= Architecture |volume=6 |page=120 |editor= Gunawan Tjahjono |year=1998 |publisher=Archipelago Press |location=Singapore | isbn = 981-3018-30-5 }}</ref> Similar with Dutch Rationalism, the style is the result of the attempt to develop new solutions to integrate traditional precedents (classicism) with new technological possibilities. It can be described as a transitional style between Traditionalists and the Modernists, and was strongly influenced by the design of [[Hendrik Petrus Berlage|Berlage]].<ref name="indische">{{cite book |last= |first= |date=1990 |title=Het Indische bouwen: architectuur en stedebouw in Indonesie : Dutch and Indisch architecture 1800-1950 |chapter=Rationalisme, Traditionalisme, Americanisme |url=https://books.google.co.id/books?id=wUa4nQEACAAJ&dq=het+indische+bouwen&hl=en&sa=X&ei=JNkYVdHMCcS2uASovIDQDg&redir_esc=y |location=Helmond |publisher=Gemeentemuseum Helmond |pages=20–23 |isbn= |access-date= |language=Dutch}}</ref>
Construction began in 1904 with A building, which was completed in 1907.{{sfn|Prihadi 2011, Lawang Sewu Kini}} The rest of the complex was finished in 1919.{{sfn|Prihadi 2011, Lawang Sewu Kini}} It was initially used by the [[Nederlandsch-Indische Spoorweg Maatschappij]], the first railway company in the [[Dutch East Indies]].{{sfn|Prihadi 2011, Lawang Sewu Kini}}
After the [[Japanese occupation of Indonesia|Japanese invaded Indonesia]] in 1942, the Japanese army took over Lawang Sewu.{{sfn|Prihadi 2011, Lawang Sewu Kini}} The basement of B building was turned into a prison, with several executions taking place there.{{sfn|Prihadi 2011, Lawang Sewu Kini}} When Semarang was retaken by the Dutch in the battle of Semarang in October 1945, the Dutch forces used the tunnel leading into A building to sneak into the city.{{sfn|Prihadi 2011, Lawang Sewu Kini}} A battle ensued, with numerous Indonesian fighters dying.{{sfn|Semarang City Government, Lawang Sewu}} Five employees working there were also killed.{{sfn|Tio|2011|p=62}}
After the war, the [[Tentara Nasional Indonesia|Indonesian army]] took over the complex.{{sfn|Tio|2011|p=62}} It was later returned to the [[PT Kereta Api|national railway company]].{{sfn|Tio|2011|p=62}} In 1992 it was declared a [[Cultural Property of Indonesia]].{{sfn|Rohmah 2013, Lawang Sewu}}
By 2009 the Lawang Sewu complex was in a state of considerable dilapidation.{{sfn|Gower 2009, Lawang Sewu: Ahaunted}} Simon Marcus Gower, writing in ''[[The Jakarta Post]]'', noted it as being "dark and evidently sick. Its white walls are faded throughout; blackened by pollution and neglect. Rendered walls are cracked and any wall paper has long since fallen away to reveal the red bricks beneath. Mould and weeds grow over much of the building and mice and rats are the chief residents."{{sfn|Gower 2009, Lawang Sewu: Ahaunted}}
The building soon underwent renovations to ensure that it would be profitable as a tourist attraction.{{sfn|Ariwibowo 2011, First Lady Inaugurates}}{{sfn|Okezone.com 2011, Banyak Warga Kecewa}} Governor of Central Java [[Bibit Waluyo]] mobilized several dozen soldiers to assist with the renovations; the soldiers focused on external repairs.{{sfn|Ariwibowo 2011, First Lady Inaugurates}} Local residents were disappointed in the renovations, opining that it had lost its authenticity.{{sfn|Okezone.com 2011, Banyak Warga Kecewa}}
On 5 July 2011 the newly renovated complex was inaugurated by First Lady [[Ani Yudhoyono]].{{sfn|Ariwibowo 2011, First Lady Inaugurates}} However, at the time only B building was available for tours.{{sfn|Prihadi 2011, Lawang Sewu Kini}} It is hoped to be a main attraction in the Central Javan government's tourism program in 2013.{{sfn|Ariwibowo 2011, First Lady Inaugurates}}
Future plans include transforming Building B into office space, a food court, and even a gym.{{sfn|Vann 2013, Haunted House}} In late 2013 the Semarang city government announced plans to eliminate the building's "spooky image" in order to attract more visitors. This was to encompass a reimagining of the site as a place for social and cultural activities, supported by renovations of the building. At the time, Lawang Sewu attracted an average of 1,000 visitors daily.{{sfn|Rohmah 2013, Lawang Sewu}}
==Urban legend== [[File:Basement of Lawang Sewu 2011.JPG|thumb|The basement of B building, said to be haunted by a kuntilbiang]] [[File:Underground Access of Lawang Sewu, Semarang, Central Java, Indonesia.jpg|thumb|An access to the underground of Lawang Sewu building in Semarang, Central Java, Indonesia]]
Lawang Sewu is said to be haunted, with many tourists visiting to see the ghosts.{{sfn|Gower 2009, Lawang Sewu: Ahaunted}} Among the ghosts reported to inhabit the establishment are a [[:wikt:Dutchwoman|Dutchwoman]] who committed suicide inside and "headless ghouls".{{sfn|Gower 2009, Lawang Sewu: Ahaunted}}
In 2007, a horror film entitled ''[[Lawang Sewu: Dendam Kuntilanak]]'' (''Lawang Sewu: Kuntilanak's Vengeance'') was released based on the legend.{{sfn|KapanLagi.com 2007, 'Lawang Sewu', Film}} It told the story of a group of high school students from [[Jakarta]] who were trapped in Lawang Sewu after several had to urinate and featured ghosts of a Dutchwoman, a man with a ball and chain wrapped around his leg, and a [[kuntilanak]].{{sfn|KapanLagi.com 2007, 'Lawang Sewu', Film}}
