{{About|a film director and producer|the British historian|Norman Cohn}}

'''Norman Cohn''' (born October 6, 1946) is a [[United States|U.S.]]-born [[Canadians|Canadian]] film director, producer, cinematographer and editor best known for his work on films ''[[Atanarjuat: The Fast Runner]]'' and ''[[The Journals of Knud Rasmussen]]''.

Born in [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States]], Cohn has lived most of his life in [[Igloolik]], [[Nunavut]] and [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], [[Canada]].

Along with director [[Zacharias Kunuk]], he co-founded the first [[Inuit]] owned (75%) [[production company]], [[Isuma]] and is the secretary-treasurer.<ref>[http://www.isuma.ca/about Isuma - About]</ref> In filming ''Atanarjuat'' in Igloolik, Cohn used natural light in shooting with his [[Sony]] DVW 700 digital camera, avoiding switches from the automatic camera settings.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Alioff|first=Maurie |date=September 2001 |title=From the Edge of the Earth: Zacharias Kunuk's ''Atanarjuat'' |magazine=[[Take One (Canadian magazine)|Take One]] |page=21}}</ref> He also edited the film with Kunuk and Marie-Christine Sarda, sharing the [[Academy of Canadian Cinema and Television Award for Best Achievement in Editing|Genie Award for Best Editing]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/inuit-film-earns-top-honours-at-genie-awards-1.345666 |title=Inuit film earns top honours at Genie Awards |last= |first= |date=8 February 2002 |accessdate=3 January 2017 |work=[[CBC News]]}}</ref> With Kunuk and director [[Natar Ungalaaq]], Cohn also helped develop the screenplay for the 2016 film ''[[Searchers (film)|Searchers]]''.<ref name="Gregoire">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nunatsiaqonline.ca/stories/article/65674nunavut_murder_drama_head_for_the_red_carpet_at_tiff/ |title=Nunavut directors head for the red carpet at TIFF |last=Gregoire |first=Lisa |date=15 August 2016 |accessdate=28 January 2017 |work=[[The Nunatsiaq News]]}}</ref>

